<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Sabah — Kota Kinabalu to Sandakan</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Sabah — Kota Kinabalu to Sandakan</h2><p><i>Malaysian Borneo · Sabah, KK to Sandakan via Kinabalu Park and Sepilok</i></p><p><b>Coast to coast across Borneo's highest mountain — orangutan rehabilitation, Sandakan war history, jungle rivers.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>251 km (156 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>March–October (drier); avoid Nov–Feb monsoon for the road but it stays passable</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Mountain road weather and landslides; long stretches of palm-oil monoculture on the eastern descent; logging trucks; river-flooding in heavy rain</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>458</td></tr></table><hr><p>Sabah, in Malaysian Borneo, has Southeast Asia's highest peak (Kinabalu, 4,095 m) at its centre, with Kota Kinabalu on the west coast and Sandakan on the east. The road across links them. Kinabalu Park (UNESCO) is a pocket of altitudinal biodiversity — 6,000+ plant species, including the giant Rafflesia (the world's largest flower) and dozens of pitcher-plant species. The Kundasang War Memorial above the foothills remembers the 1945 Sandakan Death Marches: 2,400 Australian and British POWs were marched 260 km through the jungle by their Japanese captors — six survived. Sepilok, near Sandakan, is the world's most-visited orangutan rehabilitation centre, returning rescued and orphaned orangutans to forest. The Kinabatangan River (a side-trip from Sukau) is Sabah's safari river.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Kinabalu Park HQ</b> — 1,500 m. UNESCO. Mount Kinabalu (4,095 m) climb requires a permit booked months ahead. Day visitors can walk the 11 km of trails around HQ — botanical highlights of one of Earth's most diverse mountains.</li><li><b>Kundasang War Memorial</b> — Above the village. Four gardens (Australian, British, Borneo, contemplation) commemorate the 2,400 POWs killed in the 1945 Sandakan-Ranau Death Marches and the local people who helped escapees. Kinabalu fills the western view.</li><li><b>Mesilau</b> — Highland strawberry farms and dairy (the Desa Cattle Farm — surreal Holstein cows on tropical mountain slopes). The vegetables on every Sabah dinner table mostly come from these terraces.</li><li><b>Poring Hot Springs (spur)</b> — Below Ranau on the eastern flank. Hot mineral pools developed by the Japanese during WWII; canopy walkway 40 m up in the rainforest; Rafflesia blooms here on irregular schedule (worth checking).</li><li><b>Sepilok Orangutan Rehabilitation Centre</b> — World's most famous orangutan sanctuary (1964), returning rescued orangutans to Kabili-Sepilok Forest Reserve. Feeding-platform viewings 10 AM and 3 PM. The neighboring Sun Bear Conservation Centre is also superb.</li><li><b>Sandakan</b> — Built on the timber and oil-palm trade. The Sandakan Memorial Park, on the site of the original POW camp, is restrained and powerful. St Michael's Anglican Church (1893) is the oldest stone building in Sabah.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
