<Folder><name>Waypoints</name><Placemark><name>Tamparuli</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.264700,6.153100,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Nabalu lookout</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.487800,6.050600,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Kinabalu Park HQ</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.559400,6.012500,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Kundasang</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.642800,6.023100,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mesilau</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.674700,5.985800,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Ranau</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>116.673900,5.952200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Telupid</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>117.425600,5.723900,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Beluran turnoff</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>117.752200,5.755300,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Sepilok</name><styleUrl>#wpt</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>117.948300,5.877200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder>
<Folder><name>Scenic Points</name><Placemark><name>Kinabalu Park HQ</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[1,500 m. UNESCO. Mount Kinabalu (4,095 m) climb requires a permit booked months ahead. Day visitors can walk the 11 km of trails around HQ — botanical highlights of one of Earth's most diverse mountains.]]></description><Point><coordinates>116.559400,6.012500,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Kundasang War Memorial</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Above the village. Four gardens (Australian, British, Borneo, contemplation) commemorate the 2,400 POWs killed in the 1945 Sandakan-Ranau Death Marches and the local people who helped escapees. Kinabalu fills the western view.]]></description><Point><coordinates>116.642800,6.023100,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Mesilau</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Highland strawberry farms and dairy (the Desa Cattle Farm — surreal Holstein cows on tropical mountain slopes). The vegetables on every Sabah dinner table mostly come from these terraces.]]></description><Point><coordinates>116.674700,5.985800,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Poring Hot Springs (spur)</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Below Ranau on the eastern flank. Hot mineral pools developed by the Japanese during WWII; canopy walkway 40 m up in the rainforest; Rafflesia blooms here on irregular schedule (worth checking).]]></description><Point><coordinates>116.673900,5.952200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Sepilok Orangutan Rehabilitation Centre</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[World's most famous orangutan sanctuary (1964), returning rescued orangutans to Kabili-Sepilok Forest Reserve. Feeding-platform viewings 10 AM and 3 PM. The neighboring Sun Bear Conservation Centre is also superb.]]></description><Point><coordinates>117.948300,5.877200,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark><Placemark><name>Sandakan</name><styleUrl>#poi</styleUrl><description><![CDATA[Built on the timber and oil-palm trade. The Sandakan Memorial Park, on the site of the original POW camp, is restrained and powerful. St Michael's Anglican Church (1893) is the oldest stone building in Sabah.]]></description><Point><coordinates>118.116700,5.840000,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark></Folder>
</Document></kml>
